Definition 2.45. A geometric morphism $f:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{E}$ is called totally connected if it is locally connected and the left adjoint $f_{!}$ preserves finite limits.
Definition 2.19. An element $m$ of a monoid $M$ is called right absorbing if it absorbs anything on its right, so $mn=m$ for all elements $n\in M$; left absorbing elements are defined dually. An element which is both left and right absorbing is called a zero element, because the $0$ of a commutative ring has this property in the ring’s multiplicative monoid. This final case is of the broadest interest, but since left and right absorbing elements manifest themselves very differently in $\operatorname{\mathbf{PSh}}(M)$, we study them independently. Note that if a monoid has both left absorbing element $l$ and a right absorbing element $r$, then $l=r$ is a zero element (which is automatically unique).
Definition 2.5. A Grothendieck topos $\mathcal{E}$ is called strongly compact if its global sections functor $\Gamma=\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{E}}(1,-)$ preserves filtered colimits. More generally, a geometric morphism $f:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{E}$ is called tidy if $f_{*}$ preserves filtered colimits. Thus a Grothendieck topos is strongly compact if and only if the global sections geometric morphism is tidy.
Definition 1.7 ([31, VII.6, Definition 2]). Recall that a functor $F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathbf{Set}$ is called flat (or filtering) if: 1. $F(C)\neq\varnothing$ for some object $C$ of $\mathcal{C}$; 2. for elements $a\in F(A)$ and $b\in F(B)$ there is an object $C$, morphisms $f:C\to A$ and $g:C\to B$, and an element $c\in F(C)$ such that $F(f)(c)=a$ and $F(f)(c)=b$; 3. for morphisms $f,g:B\to A$ in $\mathcal{C}$ and $b\in F(B)$ such that $F(f)(b)=F(g)(b)$, there is a morphism $h:C\to B$ and an element $c\in F(C)$ such that $fh=gh$ and $F(h)(c)=b$.
Definition 2.30. A monoid $M$ is said to satisfy the right Ore condition or is left reversible if for every $m_{1},m_{2}\in M$ there exists $m_{1}^{\prime},m_{2}^{\prime}\in M$ with $m_{1}m_{1}^{\prime}=m_{2}m_{2}^{\prime}$, or equivalently $m_{1}M\cap m_{2}M\neq\emptyset$. We employ the former terminology, as used by Johnstone in [25, Example A2.1.11]; the latter is employed by Sedaghatjoo and Khaksari in [37] and by Kilp et al. in [26].
Definition 2.1 (Cf. [25, C3.5]). A geometric morphism is atomic if its inverse image functor is logical. For a general geometric morphism this implies local connectedness. We say a Grothendieck topos is atomic if its global sections geometric morphism to $\mathbf{Set}$ is.
Definition 1.6. Let $B$ be a non-empty left $M$-set, and let $F:\operatorname{\mathbf{PSh}}(M)\to\mathbf{Set}$ be the functor $A\mapsto A\otimes_{M}B$. By Proposition 1.2, $F$ preserves the terminal object if and only if $B$ is indecomposable. $F$ preserves arbitrary limits if and only if it is indecomposable projective (this follows from e.g. [35, Section 4]). More generally, we say that $B$ is: • monomorphism-flat if $F$ preserves monomorphisms. • finitely product-flat if $F$ preserves finite products. • product-flat if $F$ preserves products. • equalizer-flat if $F$ preserves equalizers. • pullback-flat if $F$ preserves pullbacks. • flat if $F$ preserves finite limits.
Definition 2.26. Dualising Definition 2.21, we say a connected, locally connected geometric morphism $f$ is copunctually locally connected if the natural transformation $\alpha$ of Lemma 2.20 is a monomorphism. A Grothendieck topos is called copunctually locally connected if the global sections geometric morphism is copunctually locally connected, which can be interpreted in the case of $\operatorname{\mathbf{PSh}}(M)$ as ‘every component has at most one fixed point’.
Definition 2.61. Suppose $F:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{E}$ is a functor between toposes which preserves products. $F$ is sub-cartesian-closed if the comparison morphisms $\vartheta_{P,Q}$ of (6) in Section 1.1 are monomorphisms for every pair $P,Q$ of objects of $\mathcal{F}$. If $F$ moreover preserves monomorphisms and the comparison morphism $\chi$ of (8) is a monomorphism, we say $F$ is sublogical.
Definition 2.9 (See also [27, Section 2]). Let $M$ be a monoid, and $S\subseteq M$ a nonempty subset. As is standard, we write $\langle S\rangle_{M}$ for the submonoid of $M$ generated by $S$. We define $\langle{S}\rangle\rangle_{M}$ to be the smallest right-factorable subset of $M$ that contains $S$, and call this the right-factorable submonoid generated by $S$; the extra bracket on the right is intended to evoke the asymmetric extra property this submonoid satisfies compared with $\langle S\rangle_{M}$. We say that $S$ right-factorably generates $M$ if $\langle{S}\rangle\rangle_{M}=M$. We call $M$ right-factorably finitely generated if there is a finite subset $S\subseteq M$ such that $S$ right-factorably generates $M$. Dually, we can define $\langle\langle{S}\rangle_{M}$ to be the left-factorable submonoid generated by $S$, i.e. the smallest left-factorable submonoid containing $S$.
Definition 2.40. Let $f:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{E}$ be an essential geometric morphism satisfying $f_{!}(1)=1$. Observe that since colimits are stable under pullback in a topos, we have $Y\times\coprod_{i=1}^{n}1=\coprod_{i=1}^{n}Y$ for any object $Y$, so that products of this form are preserved by $f_{!}$. Thus the canonical morphisms $\vartheta_{\left(\coprod_{i=1}^{n}1\right),Y}:f_{!}(Y^{\left(\coprod_{i=1}^{n}% 1\right)})\to f_{!}(Y)^{\left(\coprod_{i=1}^{n}1\right)}$ are well-defined. When they are isomorphisms for every $n$, we say $f$ is finitely power-connected. Now suppose $f$ is a connected, locally connected geometric morphism. Then we say $f_{!}$ preserves $\mathcal{E}$-indexed powers, or that $f$ is power-connected if $\vartheta_{f^{*}(X),Y}$ is an isomorphism for all objects $X\in\mathcal{E}$ and $Y\in\mathcal{F}$. Since $f^{*}(\coprod_{i\in I}1)\cong\coprod_{i\in I}1$ in $\mathcal{F}$, this implies finite power-connectedness. Finally, suppose $f$ is strongly connected. We say $f$ is cartesian-closed-connected2For want of a better name: given the negative results of this section, we have been unable to obtain enough useful intuition about this condition in order to inform the name. if $f_{!}$ is cartesian-closed. By inspection, this implies being power-connected.
Definition 1.1. Let $B$ be a right $N$-set, and consider the functor $\mathcal{H}\!\mathit{om}_{N}(B,-):A\mapsto\mathcal{H}\!\mathit{om}_{N}(B,A)$. Then we say that $B$ is: • connected or indecomposable if $\mathcal{H}\!\mathit{om}_{N}(B,-)$ preserves arbitrary (small/set-indexed) coproducts; • projective if $\mathcal{H}\!\mathit{om}_{N}(B,-)$ preserves epimorphisms; • finitely presentable if $\mathcal{H}\!\mathit{om}_{N}(B,-)$ preserves filtered colimits.
Definition 2.42 ([37, Section 1]). Let $M$ be a monoid and $A$ a right $M$-set. We say that two elements $a,b\in A$ can be connected by a scheme of length $n$ if we can find $s_{1},\dots,s_{n},t_{1},\dots,t_{n}\in M$, $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in A$ such that $a=a_{1}s_{1},~{}a_{1}t_{1}=a_{2}s_{2},~{}\dots,~{}a_{n-1}t_{n}=a_{n}s_{n},~{}a% _{n}t_{n}=b.$
Definition 2.17 (see [25, C3.6]). A Grothendieck topos is called local if its global sections functor has a right adjoint. More generally, a geometric morphism $f:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{E}$ is local if its direct image functor $f_{*}$ has an $\mathcal{E}$-indexed right adjoint.
Definition 2.53. A more direct dual of Definition 2.17 in the context of essential geometric morphisms is the existence of an ‘extra left adjoint’. We say that a locally connected Grothendieck topos $\mathcal{E}$ with global sections morphism $f$ is colocal if the left adjoint $f_{!}$ has a further left adjoint. More generally, we might say a locally connected geometric morphism $f:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{E}$ is colocal if its left adjoint $f_{!}$ has a further $\mathcal{E}$-indexed left adjoint.
Definition 2.2. A topos $\mathcal{E}$ is Boolean if its subobject classifier is an internal Boolean algebra, or equivalently if every subobject of an object of $\mathcal{E}$ has a complement.
Definition 2.28. A topos $\mathcal{E}$ is said to be de Morgan if its subobject classifier is de Morgan as an internal Heyting algebra. Equivalently, this says that for any subobject $A$ of an object $B$ of $\mathcal{E}$, we have $(A\rightarrow 0)\cup((A\rightarrow 0)\rightarrow 0)=B$ in the Heyting algebra of subobjects of $B$.
Definition 2.58. Let $f:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{E}$ be a connected, locally connected geometric morphism. We say $f$ is bilocal if it is both local and colocal. We say $f$ is bipunctually locally connected if it is both punctually and copunctually locally connected. As usual, we say a Grothendieck topos has these properties if its global sections morphism does.
Definition 2.21. A connected, locally connected geometric morphism is said to be punctually locally connected if the natural transformation of Lemma 2.20 is epic. A connected, locally connected topos is called punctually locally connected if the global sections geometric morphism is punctually locally connected, which can be interpreted in the case of $\operatorname{\mathbf{PSh}}(M)$ as the statement ‘every component has at least one fixed point’.
Definition 2.47 (see [37], [26, III, Definition 14.1]). We say that $M$ is right collapsible if for any pair $m_{1},m_{2}$ of elements of $M$, there exists $m\in M$ with $m_{1}m=m_{2}m$, that is, if $M$ is cofiltered as a category.
Definition 2.8. Let $M$ be a monoid, and let $S\subseteq M$ be a subset. We say that $S$ is right-factorable if whenever $x\in S$ and $y\in M$ with $xy\in S$, we have $y\in S$. Dually, we may call a subset $S\subseteq M$ left-factorable if whenever $x\in M$ and $y\in S$ with $xy\in S$, we have $x\in S$.
Definition 2.34. A geometric morphism $f:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{E}$ is called strongly connected if it is locally connected and its left adjoint $f_{!}$ preserves finite products.
Definition 5.4. When $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ are pivotal dagger we restrict the 1-morphisms of $\operatorname{Fun}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D})$ and $\operatorname{Fun}_{p}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D})$ to UPTs.
Definition 2.18. Let $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ be dagger 2-categories and let $F:\mathcal{C}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{D}$ be a pseudofunctor. We say that $F$ is unitary if the following hold: • For any 2-morphism $f$, $F(f^{\dagger})=F(f)^{\dagger}$: • The multiplicators $\{m_{X,Y}\}$ and unitors $\{u_{r}\}$ are all unitary 2-morphisms in $\mathcal{D}$.
Definition 2.13. A 2-category $\mathcal{C}$ is dagger if: • For each pair of objects $r,s$ there is a contravariant identity-on-objects functor $\dagger_{r,s}:\mathcal{C}(r,s)\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{C}(r,s)$, which is involutive: for any morphism $f:X\xrightarrow{}Y$ in $\mathcal{C}(r,s)$, $\dagger_{r,s}(\dagger_{r,s}(f))=f$. (This is to say that $\mathcal{C}(r,s)$ is a dagger category.) • The dagger is compatible with composition of 1-morphisms: for any 1-morphisms $X,X^{\prime}:r\xrightarrow{}s$ and $Y,Y^{\prime}:s\xrightarrow{}t$, and 2-morphisms $\alpha:X\xrightarrow{}X^{\prime}$ and $\beta:Y\xrightarrow{}Y^{\prime}$ we have $(\alpha\circ_{H}\beta)^{\dagger_{r,t}}=\alpha^{\dagger_{r,s}}\circ_{H}\beta^{% \dagger_{s,t}}$. We call the image of a 2-morphism $f:X\xrightarrow{}Y$ under $\dagger_{r,s}$ its dagger, and write it as $f^{\dagger_{r,s}}$.
Definition 4.1. Let $F,G:\mathcal{C}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{D}$ be pseudofunctors and $\alpha:F\xrightarrow{}G$ a pseudonatural transformation. A right dual for $\alpha$ is a triple $[\alpha^{*},\eta,\epsilon]$, where $\alpha^{*}:G\xrightarrow{}F$ is a pseudonatural transformation and $\eta,\epsilon$ are modifications $\displaystyle\epsilon:\alpha\circ\alpha^{*}\xrightarrow{}\mathrm{id}_{F}$ $\displaystyle\eta:\mathrm{id}_{G}\xrightarrow{}\alpha^{*}\circ\alpha$ such that the following equations hold for any 1-morphism $X:r\xrightarrow{}s$ in $\mathcal{C}$: $\displaystyle\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/biunitarynattransfs/rightmodsnake1% 1.png}~{}~{}=~{}~{}\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/biunitarynattransfs/% rightmodsnake22.png}$ $\displaystyle\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/biunitarynattransfs/rightmodsnake2% 1.png}~{}~{}=~{}~{}\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/biunitarynattransfs/% rightmodsnake12.png}$ In the above equations we have drawn the $\alpha$-wire in green with an upwards-facing arrow and the $\alpha^{*}$-wire in green with a downwards-facing arrow, as though $\alpha_{r}$ and $\alpha_{r}^{*}$ were dual 1-morphisms. This will be justified by Lemma 4.2. A left dual is defined analogously.
Definition 2.8. We say that a 2-category $\mathcal{C}$ with right duals is pivotal if the double duals pseudofunctor is monoidally naturally isomorphic to the identity pseudofunctor.
Definition 2.15. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a dagger 2-category and let $r,s$ be objects. We say that a 1-morphism $X:r\xrightarrow{}s$ is a dagger equivalence if it is an equivalence (Definition 2.1) and the invertible 2-morphisms $\alpha:\mathrm{id}_{r}\xrightarrow{}X\circ X^{-1}$ and $\beta:\mathrm{id}_{s}\xrightarrow{}X^{-1}\circ X$ are unitary.
Definition 2.4. Let $X:r\xrightarrow{}s$ be a 1-morphism in a 2-category. A right dual $[X^{*},\eta,\epsilon]$ for $X$ is: • A 1-morphism $X^{*}:s\xrightarrow{}r$. • Two 2-morphisms $\eta:\mathrm{id}_{s}\xrightarrow{}X^{*}\circ X$ and $\epsilon:X\circ X^{*}\xrightarrow{}\mathrm{id}_{r}$ satisfying the following snake equations: $\displaystyle\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/2catsnake11.png}~{}~{}=~{}~{% }\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/2catsnake12.png}$ $\displaystyle\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/2catsnake21.png}~{}~{}=~{}~{% }\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/2catsnake22.png}$ A left dual $[{}^{*}X,\eta,\epsilon]$ is defined similarly, with 2-morphisms $\eta:\mathrm{id}_{s}\xrightarrow{}X\circ{}^{*}X$ and $\epsilon:{}^{*}X\circ X\xrightarrow{}\mathrm{id}_{r}$ satisfying the analogues of (8). We say that a 2-category $\mathcal{C}$ has right duals (resp. has left duals) if every 1-morphism $X$ in $\mathcal{C}$ has a chosen right dual $[X^{*},\eta,\epsilon]$ (resp. a chosen left dual).
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$, be 2-categories. A pseudofunctor $F:\mathcal{C}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{D}$ consists of the following data. • For each object $r$ of $\mathcal{C}$, an object $F(r)$ of $\mathcal{D}$. • For each hom-category $\mathcal{C}(r,s)$ of $\mathcal{C}$, a functor $F_{r,s}:\mathcal{C}(r,s)\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{D}(F(r),F(s))$. In the graphical calculus, we represent the effect of the functor $F_{r,s}$ by drawing a shaded box around 1- and 2-morphisms in $\mathcal{C}(r,s)$. For example, $X,Y:r\xrightarrow{}s$ be 1-morphisms and $f:X\xrightarrow{}Y$ a 2-morphism in $\mathcal{C}$. Then the 2-morphism $F(f):F(X)\xrightarrow{}F(Y)$ in $\mathcal{D}(F(r),F(s))$ is represented as: $\displaystyle\includegraphics[scale=0.8]{Figures/svg/monoidalfunctors/% boxnotation1.png}~{}~{}=~{}~{}\includegraphics[scale=0.8]{Figures/svg/% monoidalfunctors/boxnotation2.png}$ • For every pair of composable 1-morphisms $X:r\xrightarrow{}s$, $Y:s\xrightarrow{}t$ of $\mathcal{C}$, an invertible multiplicator 2-morphism $m_{X,Y}:F(X)\circ_{D}F(Y)\xrightarrow{}F(X\circ_{C}Y)$. In the graphical calculus, these 2-morphisms and their inverses are represented as follows: $\displaystyle m_{X,Y}:F(X)\circ_{\mathcal{D}}F(Y)\xrightarrow{}F(X\circ_{% \mathcal{C}}Y)$ $\displaystyle m_{X,Y}^{-1}:F(X\circ_{\mathcal{C}}Y)\xrightarrow{}F(X)\circ_{% \mathcal{D}}F(Y)$ • For every object $r$ of $\mathcal{C}$, an invertible ‘unitor’ 2-morphism $u_{r}:\mathrm{id}_{F(r)}\xrightarrow{}F(\mathrm{id}_{r})$. In the diagrammatic calculus, these 2-morphism and their inverses are represented as follows (recall that identity 1-morphisms are invisible): $\displaystyle u_{r}:\mathrm{id}_{F(r)}\xrightarrow{}F(\mathrm{id}_{r})$ $\displaystyle u^{-1}:F(\mathrm{id}_{r})\xrightarrow{}\mathrm{id}_{F(r)}$ The multiplicators and unitor must obey the following coherence equations: • Naturality. For any objects $r,s,t$, 1-morphisms $X,X^{\prime}:r\xrightarrow{}s$, $Y,Y^{\prime}:s\xrightarrow{}t$, and 2-morphisms $f:X\xrightarrow{}X^{\prime},g:Y\xrightarrow{}Y^{\prime}$ in $\mathcal{C}$: $\displaystyle\includegraphics[scale=0.8]{Figures/svg/monoidalfunctors/natural1% .png}~{}~{}=~{}~{}\includegraphics[scale=0.8]{Figures/svg/monoidalfunctors/% natural2.png}$ • Associativity. For any objects $r,s,t,u$ and 1-morphisms $X:r\xrightarrow{}s$, $Y:s\xrightarrow{}t$, $Z:t\xrightarrow{}u$ of $\mathcal{C}$: $\displaystyle\includegraphics[scale=0.8]{Figures/svg/monoidalfunctors/assoc1.% png}~{}~{}=~{}~{}\includegraphics[scale=0.8]{Figures/svg/monoidalfunctors/% assoc2.png}$ • Unitality. For any objects $r,s$ and 1-morphism $X:r\xrightarrow{}s$ of $\mathcal{C}$: $\displaystyle\includegraphics[scale=0.8]{Figures/svg/monoidalfunctors/% unitality1.png}~{}~{}=~{}~{}\includegraphics[scale=0.8]{Figures/svg/% monoidalfunctors/unitality2.png}~{}~{}=~{}~{}\includegraphics[scale=0.8]{% Figures/svg/monoidalfunctors/unitality3.png}$ We say that a pseudofunctor $F:\mathcal{C}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{D}$ is an equivalence if every object in $\mathcal{D}$ is equivalent to an object in the image of $F$ and the functors $F_{r,s}:\mathcal{C}(r,s)\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{D}(r,s)$ are equivalences.
Definition 3.3. Let $\alpha,\beta:F\Rightarrow G$ be pseudonatural transformations between pseudofunctors $F,G:\mathcal{C}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{D}$. (We colour the $\alpha$-wire green and the $\beta$-wire orange.) A modification $f:\alpha\xrightarrow{}\beta$ is defined by the following data: • For every object $r$ of $\mathcal{C}$, a 2-morphism $f_{r}:\alpha_{r}\xrightarrow{}\beta_{r}$ in $\mathcal{D}$, such that the 2-morphisms $\{f_{r}\}$ satisfy the following equation for all 1-morphisms $X:r\xrightarrow{}s$ in $\mathcal{C}$: $\displaystyle\includegraphics[scale=1]{Figures/svg/biunitarynattransfs/% modification1.png}~{}~{}=~{}~{}\includegraphics[scale=1]{Figures/svg/% biunitarynattransfs/modification2.png}$
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a 2-category and let $X:r\xrightarrow{}s$ be a 1-morphism in $\mathcal{C}$. We say that $X$ is an equivalence if there exists a 1-morphism $X^{-1}:s\xrightarrow{}r$, and invertible2I.e. invertible in the Hom-categories $\mathcal{C}(r,s)$ and $\mathcal{C}(s,r)$. We sometimes call an invertible 2-morphism a 2-isomorphism. 2-morphisms $\alpha:\mathrm{id}_{r}\xrightarrow{}X\circ X^{-1}$ and $\beta:\mathrm{id}_{s}\xrightarrow{}X^{-1}\circ X$. In diagrams, the equations for invertibility of $\alpha,\beta$ are as follows, where $\alpha^{-1},\beta^{-1}$ are the inverse 2-morphisms: $\displaystyle\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/equiva11.png}=% \includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/equiva12.png},$ $\displaystyle~{}~{}\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/equiva21.png}=% \includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/equiva22.png},$ $\displaystyle\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/equivb11.png}=% \includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/equivb12.png},$ $\displaystyle~{}~{}\includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/equivb21.png}=% \includegraphics[]{Figures/svg/2cats/equivb22.png}$ If there exists an equivalence $X:r\xrightarrow{}s$ we say that the objects $r$ and $s$ are equivalent in $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ be 2-categories. The 2-category $\operatorname{Fun}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D})$ is defined as follows: • Objects: monoidal functors $F,G,\dots,\cdot:\mathcal{C}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{D}$. • 1-morphisms: pseudonatural transformations $\alpha,\beta,\dots:F\xrightarrow{}G$. • 2-morphisms: modifications $f,g,\dots:\alpha\xrightarrow{}\beta$. Because we are able to assume that $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ are strict, $\operatorname{Fun}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D})$ is also strict.
Definition 2.12 ([9, §1.7.5]). Let $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ be pivotal dagger 2-categories, and let $F:\mathcal{C}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{D}$ be a pseudofunctor, and let $F_{l},F_{r}:F(X^{*})\xrightarrow{}F(X)^{*}$ be the isomorphisms (14). We say that $F$ is pivotal if $F_{l}=F_{r}=:P$.
Definition 5.3. Let $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ be pivotal dagger 2-categories and let $F,G:\mathcal{C}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{D}$ be unitary pseudofunctors. Then a unitary pseudonatural transformation (UPT) $\alpha:F\xrightarrow{}G$ is a pseudonatural transformation such that either of the following equivalent conditions are satisfied: • There is an equality of pseudonatural transformations $\alpha^{*}=\alpha^{\dagger}$. • For all 1-morphisms $X:r\xrightarrow{}s$ in $\mathcal{C}$, the component $\alpha_{X}:F(X)\circ\alpha_{r}\xrightarrow{}\alpha_{s}\circ G(X)$ is unitary.
