Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ be 2-categories, and let $F,G:\mathcal{C}\xrightarrow{}\mathcal{D}$ be pseudofunctors (depicted by blue and red boxes respectively). A pseudonatural transformation $\alpha:F\xrightarrow{}G$ is defined by the following data: • For every object $r$ of $\mathcal{C}$, a 1-morphism $\alpha_{r}:F(r)\xrightarrow{}G(r)$ of $\mathcal{D}$ (drawn as a green wire). • For every 1-morphism $X:r\xrightarrow{}s$ of $\mathcal{C}$, a 2-morphism $\alpha_{X}:F(X)\circ\alpha_{s}\xrightarrow{}\alpha_{r}\circ G(X)$ (drawn as a white vertex): The 2-morphisms $\alpha_{X}$ must satisfy the following conditions: • Naturality. For every 2-morphism $f:X\xrightarrow{}Y$ in $\mathcal{C}$: $\displaystyle\includegraphics[scale=1]{Figures/svg/biunitarynattransfs/nat1.% png}~{}~{}=~{}~{}\includegraphics[scale=1]{Figures/svg/biunitarynattransfs/nat% 2.png}$ • Monoidality. – For every pair of 1-morphisms $X:r\xrightarrow{}s,Y:s\xrightarrow{}t$ in $\mathcal{C}$: $\displaystyle\includegraphics[scale=.9]{Figures/svg/biunitarynattransfs/% monoidal1.png}~{}~{}=~{}~{}\includegraphics[scale=.9]{Figures/svg/% biunitarynattransfs/monoidal2.png}$ – For every object $r$ of $\mathcal{C}$: $\displaystyle\includegraphics[scale=1]{Figures/svg/biunitarynattransfs/% unitality1.png}~{}~{}=~{}~{}\includegraphics[scale=1]{Figures/svg/% biunitarynattransfs/unitality2.png}$ (Equation (18) already implies the analogous pullthroughs for the comultiplicators $\{m_{X,Y}^{-1}\}$.) If $\alpha_{r}=\mathrm{id}_{F(r)}$ for every object $r$ of $\mathcal{C}$, we say that $\alpha$ is a monoidal natural transformation. (Definition 2.8 is now complete.)
Definition 2.14. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a dagger 2-category. We say that a 2-morphism $\alpha:X\xrightarrow{}Y$ in $\mathcal{C}(r,s)$ is an isometry if $\alpha\circ_{V}\alpha^{\dagger_{r,s}}=\mathrm{id}_{X}$. We say that it is unitary if it is an isometry and additionally $\alpha^{\dagger_{r,s}}\circ_{V}\alpha=\mathrm{id}_{Y}$.
Definition 4.7. When $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ are pivotal we define $\operatorname{Fun}_{p}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D})\subset\operatorname{Fun}(% \mathcal{C},\mathcal{D})$ to be the subcategory whose objects are pivotal pseudofunctors.
Definition 4.15. For any $\delta_{1},\delta_{2}\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$, define $\delta_{1}+\delta_{2}\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ by $\delta_{1}+\delta_{2}=(\nabla_{A})_{\ast}(\Delta_{C})^{\ast}(\delta_{1}\oplus% \delta_{2}).$ Obviously this operation is commutative.
Definition 3.22. An exact sequence $\mathbf{S}$ is said to split, if it satisfies condition (iii) (or other equivalent conditions) in Corollary 3.21.
Definition 4.3. $($[NP, Definition 2.12]$)$ A triplet $(h\mathscr{C},\mathbb{E},\mathfrak{s})$ is called an extriangulated category if it satisfies the following conditions. In this case, the pair $(\mathbb{E},\mathfrak{s})$ is called an external triangulation of $h\mathscr{C}$. (ET1) $\mathbb{E}\colon(h\mathscr{C})^{\mathrm{op}}\times(h\mathscr{C})\to\mathit{Ab}$ is a biadditive functor. (ET2) $\mathfrak{s}$ is an additive realization of $\mathbb{E}$. (ET3) Let $\delta\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ and $\delta^{\prime}\in\mathbb{E}(C^{\prime},A^{\prime})$ be any pair of elements with $(\ref{PairReal})$. Then, for any commutative square $\xy(-12,6)*+{A}="0";(0,6)*+{B}="2";(12,6)*+{C}="4";(-12,-6)*+{A^{\prime}}="10"% ;(0,-6)*+{B^{\prime}}="12";(12,-6)*+{C^{\prime}}="14";{\ar^{\mathfrak{x}}"0";"% 2"};{\ar^{\mathfrak{y}}"2";"4"};{\ar_{\mathfrak{a}}"0";"10"};{\ar^{\mathfrak{b% }}"2";"12"};{\ar_{\mathfrak{x}^{\prime}}"10";"12"};{\ar_{\mathfrak{y}^{\prime}% }"12";"14"};{\ar@{}|{\circlearrowright}"0";"12"};\endxy$ in $h\mathscr{C}$, there exists $\mathfrak{c}\in(h\mathscr{C})(C,C^{\prime})$ such that $\mathfrak{c}\circ\mathfrak{y}=\mathfrak{y}^{\prime}\circ\mathfrak{b}$ and $\mathbb{E}(C,\mathfrak{a})(\delta)=\mathbb{E}(\mathfrak{c},A^{\prime})(\delta^% {\prime})$. (ET3)${}^{\mathrm{op}}$ Dual of (ET3). (ET4) Let $\delta\in\mathbb{E}(D,A)$ and $\delta^{\prime}\in\mathbb{E}(F,B)$ be any pair of elements, with $\mathfrak{s}(\delta)=[A\overset{\mathfrak{f}}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{% \mathfrak{f}^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}D]\ \ \text{and}\ \ \mathfrak{s}(\delta% ^{\prime})=[B\overset{\mathfrak{g}}{\longrightarrow}C\overset{\mathfrak{g}^{% \prime}}{\longrightarrow}F].$ Then there exist an object $E\in h\mathscr{C}$, a commutative diagram $\xy(-18,6)*+{A}="0";(-6,6)*+{B}="2";(6,6)*+{D}="4";(-18,-6)*+{A}="10";(-6,-6)*% +{C}="12";(6,-6)*+{E}="14";(-6,-18)*+{F}="22";(6,-18)*+{F}="24";{\ar^{% \mathfrak{f}}"0";"2"};{\ar^{\mathfrak{f}^{\prime}}"2";"4"};{\ar@{=}"0";"10"};{% \ar_{\mathfrak{g}}"2";"12"};{\ar^{\mathfrak{d}}"4";"14"};{\ar_{\mathfrak{h}}"1% 0";"12"};{\ar_{\mathfrak{h}^{\prime}}"12";"14"};{\ar_{\mathfrak{g}^{\prime}}"1% 2";"22"};{\ar^{\mathfrak{e}}"14";"24"};{\ar@{=}"22";"24"};{\ar@{}|{% \circlearrowright}"0";"12"};{\ar@{}|{\circlearrowright}"2";"14"};{\ar@{}|{% \circlearrowright}"12";"24"};\endxy$ in $h\mathscr{C}$, and an element $\delta^{\prime\prime}\in\mathbb{E}(E,A)$ such that $\mathfrak{s}(\delta^{\prime\prime})=[A\overset{\mathfrak{h}}{\longrightarrow}C% \overset{\mathfrak{h}^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}E]$, which satisfy the following compatibilities. (i) $\mathfrak{s}(\mathbb{E}(F,\mathfrak{f}^{\prime})(\delta^{\prime}))=[D\overset{% \mathfrak{d}}{\longrightarrow}E\overset{\mathfrak{e}}{\longrightarrow}F]$, (ii) $\mathbb{E}(\mathfrak{d},A)(\delta^{\prime\prime})=\delta$, (iii) $\mathbb{E}(E,\mathfrak{f})(\delta^{\prime\prime})=\mathbb{E}(\mathfrak{e},B)(% \delta^{\prime})$. (ET4)${}^{\mathrm{op}}$ Dual of (ET4).
Definition 3.1. ([B1, Definition 3.1]) The triplet $(\mathscr{C},\mathscr{C}_{{\dagger}},\mathscr{C}^{{\dagger}})$ is an exact quasi-category ($=$ exact $\infty$-category) if it satisfies the following conditions. (Ex0) $\mathscr{C}$ is additive. (Ex1) If $O\in\mathscr{C}_{0}$ is a zero object, then any morphism $O\to X$ in $\mathscr{C}$ is ingressive. Dually, any morphism $X\to O$ in $\mathscr{C}$ is egressive. (Ex2) Push-outs of ingressive morphisms exist and are ingressive. Dually, pull-backs of egressive morphisms exist and are egressive. (Ex3) A square in $\mathscr{C}$ is an ambigressive pull-back if and only if it is an ambigressive push-out.
Definition 4.9. Functor $\mathbb{E}\colon(h\mathscr{C})^{\mathrm{op}}\times h\mathscr{C}\to\mathit{Set}$ is defined by the following. • For an object $(C,A)\in(h\mathscr{C})^{\mathrm{op}}\times(h\mathscr{C})$, the set $\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ is the one defined in Definition 4.4. • For a morphism $(\mathfrak{c},\mathfrak{a})\in\big{(}(h\mathscr{C})^{\mathrm{op}}\times(h% \mathscr{C})\big{)}\big{(}(C,A),(C^{\prime},A^{\prime})\big{)}$, the map $\mathbb{E}(\mathfrak{c},\mathfrak{a})\colon\mathbb{E}(C,A)\to\mathbb{E}(C^{% \prime},A^{\prime})$ is the one defined by $\mathbb{E}(\mathfrak{c},\mathfrak{a})=\mathfrak{c}^{\ast}\mathfrak{a}_{\ast}=% \mathfrak{a}_{\ast}\mathfrak{c}^{\ast}$.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathscr{E}\subseteq\mathrm{Fun}(\Delta^{1}\times\Delta^{1},\mathscr{C})$ be the full subcategory spanned by exact sequences. In particular, for a pair of exact sequences $\mathbf{S}=\ \xy(-7,7)*+{A}="0";(7,7)*+{B}="2";(-7,-7)*+{O}="4";(7,-7)*+{C}="6% ";{\ar^{x}"0";"2"};{\ar_{i}"0";"4"};{\ar|*+{{}_{z}}"0";"6"};{\ar^{y}"2";"6"};{% \ar_{j}"4";"6"};(3,7)*+{}="00";(7,3)*+{}="01";{\ar@/_{0}.2pc/@{-}_{{}^{\xi}}"0% 0";"01"};(-3,-7)*+{}="10";(-7,-3)*+{}="11";{\ar@/_{0}.2pc/@{-}_{{}_{\eta}}"10"% ;"11"};\endxy\quad\text{and}\quad\mathbf{S}^{\prime}=\ \xy(-7,7)*+{A^{\prime}}% ="0";(7,7)*+{B^{\prime}}="2";(-7,-7)*+{O^{\prime}}="4";(7,-7)*+{C^{\prime}}="6% ";{\ar^{x^{\prime}}"0";"2"};{\ar_{i^{\prime}}"0";"4"};{\ar|*+{{}_{z^{\prime}}}% "0";"6"};{\ar^{y^{\prime}}"2";"6"};{\ar_{j^{\prime}}"4";"6"};(3,7)*+{}="00";(7% ,3)*+{}="01";{\ar@/_{0}.2pc/@{-}_{(}0.4){{}^{\xi^{\prime}}}"00";"01"};(-3,-7)*% +{}="10";(-7,-3)*+{}="11";{\ar@/_{0}.2pc/@{-}_{(}0.4){{}_{\eta^{\prime}}}"10";% "11"};\endxy,$ a morphism of exact sequences from $\mathbf{S}$ to $\mathbf{S}^{\prime}$ means a cube $\mathbf{C}=\ \xy(-8,9)*+{A}="0";(8,9)*+{B}="2";(1,3)*+{O}="4";(17,3)*+{C}="6";% (-8,-7)*+{A^{\prime}}="10";(8,-7)*+{B^{\prime}}="12";(1,-13)*+{O^{\prime}}="14% ";(17,-13)*+{C^{\prime}}="16";{\ar^{x}"0";"2"};{\ar_{i}"0";"4"};{\ar^{y}"2";"6% "};{\ar_{(}0.3){j}"4";"6"};{\ar_{a}"0";"10"};{\ar^{(}0.7){b}|!{(9,3);(13,3)}% \hole"2";"12"};{\ar_{(}0.3){o}"4";"14"};{\ar^{c}"6";"16"};{\ar^{(}0.3){x^{% \prime}}|!{(1,-3);(1,-7)}\hole"10";"12"};{\ar_{i^{\prime}}"10";"14"};{\ar^{y^{% \prime}}"12";"16"};{\ar_{j^{\prime}}"14";"16"};\endxy$ which satisfies $\mathbf{C}|_{\Delta^{1}\times\Delta^{1}\times\{0\}}=\mathbf{S}$ and $\mathbf{C}|_{\Delta^{1}\times\Delta^{1}\times\{1\}}=\mathbf{S}^{\prime}$. We abbreviate this to $\mathbf{C}\colon\mathbf{S}\to\mathbf{S}^{\prime}$. When we indicate morphisms $a$ and $c$, we will also write ${}_{a}\mathbf{C}_{c}\colon\mathbf{S}\to\mathbf{S}^{\prime}$ in this article.
Definition 4.23. Inspired from [S], we call topological any extriangulated category which is equivalent to the homotopy category of an exact quasi-category.
Definition 4.1. $($[NP, Definition 2.7]$)$ For a pair of objects $A,C\in h\mathscr{C}$, two consecutive morphisms $A\overset{\mathfrak{x}}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{\mathfrak{y}}{% \longrightarrow}C$ and $A\overset{\mathfrak{x}^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}B^{\prime}\overset{\mathfrak{% y}^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}C$ are said to be equivalent if there is an isomorphism $\mathfrak{b}\in(h\mathscr{C})(B,B^{\prime})$ such that $\mathfrak{b}\circ\mathfrak{x}=\mathfrak{x}^{\prime}$ and $\mathfrak{y}^{\prime}\circ\mathfrak{b}=\mathfrak{y}$. In the sequel, the equivalence class to which a sequence $A\overset{\mathfrak{x}}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{\mathfrak{y}}{% \longrightarrow}C$ belongs will be denoted by $[A\overset{\mathfrak{x}}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{\mathfrak{y}}{% \longrightarrow}C]$.
Definition 4.27 ([B-TS, Definition 2.31]). A functor $G\colon(\mathcal{C},\mathbb{E},\mathfrak{s})\to(\mathcal{D},\mathbb{E}^{\prime% },\mathfrak{s}^{\prime})$ between extriangulated categories is exact (or extriangulated) if it is additive, and if there is a natural transformation $\Gamma\colon\mathbb{E}\Rightarrow\mathbb{E}^{\prime}(G^{\mathrm{op}}-,G-)$ such that, for any $\mathfrak{s}$-triangle $A\overset{i}{\rightarrowtail}B\overset{p}{\twoheadrightarrow}C\overset{\delta}% {\dashrightarrow}$ in $\mathcal{C}$, its image $GA\overset{Gi}{\rightarrowtail}GB\overset{Gp}{\twoheadrightarrow}GC\overset{% \Gamma_{C,A}(\delta)}{\dashrightarrow}$ is an $\mathfrak{s}^{\prime}$-triangle in $\mathcal{D}$.
Definition 4.2. $($[NP, Definitions 2.9 and 2.10]$)$ Suppose that there is a biadditive functor $\mathbb{E}\colon(h\mathscr{C})^{\mathrm{op}}\times(h\mathscr{C})\to\mathit{Ab}$ to the category of abelian groups $\mathit{Ab}$. Let $\mathfrak{s}$ be a correspondence which associates an equivalence class $\mathfrak{s}(\delta)=[A\overset{\mathfrak{x}}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{% \mathfrak{y}}{\longrightarrow}C]$ to each element $\delta\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$. Such $\mathfrak{s}$ is called an additive realization of $\mathbb{E}$ if it satisfies the following conditions. (i) Let $\delta\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ and $\delta^{\prime}\in\mathbb{E}(C^{\prime},A^{\prime})$ be any pair of elements, with $\mathfrak{s}(\delta)=[A\overset{\mathfrak{x}}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{% \mathfrak{y}}{\longrightarrow}C],\ \ \mathfrak{s}(\delta^{\prime})=[A^{\prime}% \overset{\mathfrak{x}^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}B^{\prime}\overset{\mathfrak{y% }^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}C^{\prime}].$ Then, for any pair of morphisms $\mathfrak{a}\in(h\mathscr{C})(A,A^{\prime}),\mathfrak{c}\in(h\mathscr{C})(C,C^% {\prime})$ satisfying $\mathbb{E}(C,\mathfrak{a})(\delta)=\mathbb{E}(\mathfrak{c},A^{\prime})(\delta^% {\prime})$, there exists a morphism $\mathfrak{b}\in(h\mathscr{C})(B,B^{\prime})$ such that $\mathfrak{b}\circ\mathfrak{x}=\mathfrak{x}^{\prime}\circ\mathfrak{a}$ and $\mathfrak{y}^{\prime}\circ\mathfrak{b}=\mathfrak{c}\circ\mathfrak{y}$. (ii) For any $A,C\in h\mathscr{C}$, the zero element $0\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ satisfies $\mathfrak{s}(0)=[A\overset{\left[\begin{smallmatrix}1\\ 0\end{smallmatrix}\right]}{\longrightarrow}A\oplus C\overset{[0\ 1]}{% \longrightarrow}C].$ (iii) For any pair of elements $\delta\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ and $\delta^{\prime}\in\mathbb{E}(C^{\prime},A^{\prime})$ with $(\ref{PairReal})$, we have $\mathfrak{s}(\delta\oplus\delta^{\prime})=[A\oplus A^{\prime}\overset{% \mathfrak{x}\oplus\mathfrak{x}^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}B\oplus B^{\prime}% \overset{\mathfrak{y}\oplus\mathfrak{y}^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}C\oplus C^{% \prime}].$ Here $\delta\oplus\delta^{\prime}\in\mathbb{E}(C\oplus C^{\prime},A\oplus A^{\prime})$ denotes the element which corresponds to $(\delta,0,0,\delta^{\prime})$ through the natural isomorphism $\mathbb{E}(C\oplus C^{\prime},A\oplus A^{\prime})\cong\mathbb{E}(C,A)\oplus% \mathbb{E}(C,A^{\prime})\oplus\mathbb{E}(C^{\prime},A)\oplus\mathbb{E}(C^{% \prime},A^{\prime})$ induced from the biadditivity of $\mathbb{E}$. If $\mathfrak{s}$ is an additive realization, any pair $(A\overset{\mathfrak{x}}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{\mathfrak{y}}{% \longrightarrow}C,\delta)$ of a sequence $A\overset{\mathfrak{x}}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{\mathfrak{y}}{% \longrightarrow}C$ and an element $\delta\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ satisfying $\mathfrak{s}(\delta)=[A\overset{\mathfrak{x}}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{% \mathfrak{y}}{\longrightarrow}C]$ is called an $\mathfrak{s}$-triangle (or simply an extriangle if $\mathfrak{s}$ is obvious from the context), and abbreviately expressed by $A\overset{\mathfrak{x}}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{\mathfrak{y}}{% \longrightarrow}C\overset{\delta}{\dashrightarrow}$.
